@startuml cross-instance-async-flow
'──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
' Quarkus SSE PoC — Cross-Instance Async Flow
'
' Scenario: Nginx (round-robin) routes POST and GET SSE to DIFFERENT instances.
'   POST /api/pdf/generate  → app-2  (10.89.0.9:8080)
'   GET  /api/pdf/status/…  → app-1  (10.89.0.8:8080)
'
' Observed log timestamp range: 13:27:25 – 13:27:30 (UTC)
' Process ID: 7f390554-6ca2-4eae-bdc2-4ccee13fa9d7  (abbreviated → 7f390554)
'──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

title Quarkus SSE PoC — Cross-Instance Async Flow\n(POST → app-2 | SSE stream → app-1)

skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 1.5
skinparam sequenceGroupBorderThickness 1
skinparam sequenceLifeLineBorderColor #555555
skinparam sequenceParticipantBorderColor #333333
skinparam sequenceParticipantBackgroundColor #F8F8F8
skinparam noteBorderColor #AAAAAA
skinparam noteBackgroundColor #FFFFF0

actor       "Browser\n(Client)"          as C

box "Nginx\n(reverse proxy / LB)" #EEF4FF
  participant "Nginx"                    as N
end box

box "app-2  (10.89.0.9:8080)" #FFF4EE
  participant "PdfResource"              as PR2
  participant "Vert.x EventBus"          as EB2
  participant "PdfEventProcessor"        as PEP2
  participant "SseBroadcaster\n(app-2)"  as SSB2
end box

box "Infrastructure" #F0FFF0
  participant "MinIO"                    as M
  participant "Redis\n(Pub/Sub)"         as R
end box

box "app-1  (10.89.0.8:8080)" #EEF4FF
  participant "SseBroadcaster\n(app-1)"  as SSB1
  participant "PdfResource"              as PR1
end box

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [1] PDF Generation Request  (13:27:25.313) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

C  ->  N   : POST /api/pdf/generate
note right of N
  Nginx routes to **app-2**
  (round-robin upstream: 10.89.0.9:8080)
end note

N  ->  PR2 : POST /api/pdf/generate
activate PR2

PR2 -> PR2 : generate processId\n**7f390554**
PR2 ->  EB2 : publish PdfGenerationRequest\n(processId=7f390554)
PR2 -->  N  : **200 OK** { processId }
deactivate PR2

N  -->  C  : **200 OK** { processId }

EB2 ->  PEP2 : deliver PdfGenerationRequest
activate PEP2
PEP2 -> PEP2 : schedule PDF generation\n(delay = 5 s)
note right of PEP2 #FFF4EE
  PdfEventProcessor parks the task
  on a worker thread pool.
  Processing will complete ~13:27:30.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [2] SSE Stream Registration  (13:27:25.338) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

C  ->  N   : GET /api/pdf/status/**7f390554**
note right of N
  Nginx routes to **app-1**
  (round-robin upstream: 10.89.0.8:8080)
  — different instance from the POST!
end note

N  ->  PR1 : GET /api/pdf/status/7f390554
activate PR1

PR1 ->  SSB1 : createStream(7f390554)
activate SSB1
SSB1 -> SSB1 : register MultiEmitter\nin local processors map\n(key = 7f390554)
SSB1 -> SSB1 : checkPendingEvents(7f390554)\n→ nothing in Redis yet

PR1 --> N   : **200 SSE** (text/event-stream, chunked)
deactivate PR1

N  --> C   : **200 SSE stream open** ← waiting for events…

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [3] PDF Processing  (13:27:30.735  — 5 s later) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PEP2 ->  M  : upload PDF\n(key: 7f390554.pdf)
M   --> PEP2 : **upload OK**

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [4] Redis Pub/Sub Notification  (13:27:30.736–738) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PEP2 ->  R  : PUBLISH **custom-pdf-completed-destination**\n{ processId: 7f390554, key: 7f390554.pdf }
note right of PEP2 #FFF4EE
  Log: "null receivers" — Redis async callback
  returns null; actual delivery confirmed
  by app-1 subscriber (see below).
end note

deactivate PEP2

R   --> SSB1 : message received\n(app-1 is subscribed)
R   --> SSB2 : message received\n(app-2 is also subscribed)

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [5a] app-1 — SSE Event Delivery  (13:27:30.737) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SSB1 -> SSB1 : lookup processors map\n→ **processor found** for 7f390554 ✅
SSB1 -->  C  : SSE event:\nevent: **PDF_COMPLETED**\ndata: { processId, minioKey }
note left of C
  Browser EventSource fires
  a "PDF_COMPLETED" message event.
  SSE connection can now be closed.
end note

SSB1 -> SSB1 : onCancellation callback\n→ remove processor for 7f390554
deactivate SSB1

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [5b] app-2 — Defensive Buffer (race-condition guard)  (13:27:30.738) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SSB2 -> SSB2 : lookup processors map\n→ **no processor** for 7f390554 ⚠️
note right of SSB2 #FFF4EE
  app-2 never hosted the SSE stream
  for this processId.  It cannot know
  whether app-1 already delivered it.
end note

SSB2 ->  R  : SETEX **pending:completed:7f390554**\n{ event payload }  TTL = 300 s
note right of R #FFFFF0
  Defensive buffer: if the SSE client
  had NOT yet connected, the next call
  to createStream() on ANY instance
  would consume this via GETDEL (atomic).
  Here the event was already delivered
  by app-1 → the key will simply expire
  after 300 s with no consumer.
end note

R  --> SSB2 : **OK** (key stored)

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
== [6] SSE Stream Closed  (13:27:30.749) ==
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

N  --> C   : HTTP/1.1 **200** (SSE stream closed)\nupstream=10.89.0.8:8080

@enduml

